<a href="javascript:card_browser(235)">Anduin Banks</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(240)">Emyn Muil</a><br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(193)">Sam, Son of Hamfast</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(299)">Aragorn, Ranger of the North</a> x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(189)">Pippin, Hobbit of Some Intelligence</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(260)">Legolas, Greenleaf</a><br>
Gimli, Dwarf of the Mountain-Race<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(164)">Thrarin, Dwarven Smith</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(304)">Athelas</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(180)">Hobbit Sword</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(194)">Sting</a><br>
Rangers Sword<br>
Aragorns Bow<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(305)">Blade of Gondor</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(937)">Flaming Brand</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a> x2<br>
Mithril Coat<br>
Thrors Map<br>
Saga of Elendil<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(170)">Bounder</a> x2<br>
Farmer Maggot x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(876)">Stout and Sturdy</a> x2<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(24)">Lurtz, Servant of Isengard</a> x2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(39)">Troop of Uruk-hai</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(856)">Uruk Warrior</a> x4<br>
Uruk Captain x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(311)">Uruk Lieutenant</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(952)">Uruk Scout</a><br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(998)">Tower Assassin</a> x2<br>
Sarumans Ambition x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(36)">Spies of Saruman</a> x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(855)">Savagery to Match Their Numbers</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(944)">Beyond the Height of Men</a> x2<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> PLEASE READ BEFORE REVIEWING<br>
<br>
This is my version of the extremely powerful Merry Superstar (AKA When Hobbits Attack) archetype.  It sports an Isengard Shadow as opposed to the usual Moria Swarm.  Also, I dont play any Hobbit Stealths, because I find that extra companions are more useful.<br>
<br>
What does it do?<br>
<br>
The fellowship begins in the lead.  The Shadow holds it.  The fellowship wins by winning skirmishes and having too many companions to deal with, so I dont have to worry about getting overwhelmed.  And while Im on the topic of getting overwhelmed, using Stout and Sturdy, Ive overwhelmed the Cave Troll.  The Shadow uses strong, cheap, Damage +1 minions and numerous strength pumpers to keep the opposing fellowship at bay.  Still, even though Isengards attrition is incredible, you should focus on the fellowship.  Its going to win you the game.<br>
<br>
But Theres No Condition Removal<br>
<br>
This is the biggest knock against my deck.  Yes, this deck does indeed lack support area condition removal, so I have no way to remove Orc Bowmen, Goblin Armories, etc. and that can mean danger against a Moria or Sauron deck.  However, I have many means by which to place or heal wounds.  So, I dont have to worry about Sauron.  AND I have the potential to block many many orcs, so I shouldnt have to worry about swarms . . . so my answer to you is that I dont need condition removal when my strategy deals with those conditions.  This decks performance reflects that.  It has yet to lose a game, and Ive tested it against both Sauron and Moria.<br>
<br>
Some Card Choice Notes<br>
<br>
The Saga of Elendil: Who tells the Saga (Boromir or Aragorn) depends largely on when you get it.  If you get the Saga in the early game, its probably best to put it on Boromir so that you will be able to pump up your fellowship more effectively throughout the path.  However, if you get it in the late game, you had probably best give it to Aragorn so that he can shoot/block more minions.<br>
<br>
Stout and Sturdy:  This card is the deck.  By exerting twice with Merry, you can pump any companion to make him win a skirmish.  With 1 Stout and Sturdy, you can double exert to turn 1 Boromir exertion into 6 power for any companion.  Heres a simple example.  Your opponent is playing Moria Swarms.  Your opponent gets a Goblin Scavenger, a Moria Scout with a Scimitar, and a Runner with a Scimitar along with 2 other orcs against your 4 companion fellowship.  You double exert Aragorn (carrying his sword and a Flaming Brand) to make him Defender +2 and have him take the 3 mentioned orcs.  You assign Boromir to a skirmish that you know he will win and Frodo to anything save possibly the cave troll or Balrog (and even then maybe).  You might have to exert Boromir and/or Bounder to keep Frodo alive, but its relatively risk free.  Then, you exert Boromir to add to Merrys power.  You double exert Merry, Stout and Sturdy, and double exert again.  Aragorns a 27 power to the orcs combined 25.  Aragorn wins and all 3 orcs take 2 wounds.  Now, given the power of Stout and Sturdy, you might be wondering why I dont play more.  Well, you dont use it often, at all--generally only once from 4-6 and again from 7-9.  So, having 3 might be nice, but certainly no more than that.<br>
<br>
Athelas x4: This deck relies heavily on exertions.  That means it also relies heavily on keeping my companions fairly fresh.  Multiple Atheli are the only means by which I can guarantee that I get to heal the companions I want to when I want to.  Furthermore, they also derail Sauron Burdening strategies and Nazgul with Breaths and Tips.<br>
<br>
The Extra Companions:  These companions are here for utility and to take the heat off of Boromir and Aragorn.  I should almost always have 5 companions out, and any of these extra companions will give me a little extra advantage.  Obviously, we start with Sam, who grabs me the lead from the beginning.  Legolas can take care of 1-3 minions--shoot a couple and block another.  If I get Gimli early, he will deny my opponent twilight in Moria.  And Pippin, oddly enough, is probably the most resilient and welcome addition of all my supplementary companions.  Why?  Because of his ability and high vitality.  He doesnt get overwhelmed because of Boromir and Bounder, so that means he can take a lot of heat off of my fellowship.  Finally, Thrarin is a welcome addition as my surrogate companion.  These extra guys give me a lot of room for error.<br>
<br>
The Shadow Side:  The shadow side works together as a whole.  The Troops win skirmishes against everybody except maybe a fully juiced Gandalf or a Last Alliance assisted Gondor Companion.  The Uruk Captains are as good as 2 minions.  The Spies (with some help from the Wilderland and the Uruk Scout) keep my minions alive by avoiding ARV and archery.  But most importantly, my minions are cheap and powerful . . . a very dangerous combination that slows opposing fellowships to a crawl.<br>
<br>
So, how do I play it?<br>
Bid 4-6.  That should be enough to win the bid.  Pull Sam and remove Burdens.  Starting in the lead is key.  Use Boromir and Merry to protect you at the early sites until you get some more companions to support you.  When you do get more companions play them and take control of all skirmishes.  Win the ones you need to, kill the companions you need to, and make your opponent play reactively . . . your opponent should never break through against Aragorn, Merry, or Frodo (even Boromir is expendable to some extent).  Move at whatever pace your shadow side sets and get to 9 first.  At 9, exert Aragorn to take as many minions as he can/needs to.  <br>
<br>
On the flip side, play whatever cards you can.  Take control of your skirmishes again.  With powerful cheap minions and no Archery phase, your Uruk-hai will reign supreme.  Isengard kills more companions than any other shadow side and that is the strongest deterrent against an opposing double move.  Put your opponent on the defensive and youve got an easy win under your belt.<br>
<br>
Anyway, thats the deck.  Its lots of fun.  Constructive criticism is always welcome.  Enjoy.<br>
<br>
Devon Whatcha gonna do, brother, when Merry and Aragorn run wild on you? Clark<br>
